,"marks":1,"options":["C5","C6","C7","C8","T1"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EC6 dermatome\u003C/strong\u003E supplies sensation to the lateral aspect of the forearm and the thumb (Image). This is a key anatomical relationship that helps localise neurological lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other dermatomes supply different regions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC5 dermatome\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the lateral aspect of the upper arm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC7 dermatome\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the middle finger and central aspect of the forearm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC8 dermatome\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the medial forearm and little finger\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET1 dermatome\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the medial aspect of the upper arm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding dermatome distribution is essential for clinical practice as it helps identify the level of nerve root involvement in conditions such as cervical radiculopathy or spinal cord injury. It is important to note that there is significant overlap between adjacent dermatomes, meaning that complete loss of sensation in an area typically indicates damage to multiple spinal nerves.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The dermatomes of the upper limb originate from spinal nerves C5-T1","C5 supplies the lateral upper arm, C6 the lateral forearm and thumb, C7 the middle finger, C8 the medial forearm and little finger, and T1 the medial upper arm","Adjacent dermatomes overlap significantly, requiring damage to multiple spinal nerves to produce complete sensory loss in an area"],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cDermatomes radiculaires humains\u201d by CYP3A42D6 is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 4.0 Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Dermatomes_radiculaires_humains.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63596"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17564"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21336"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21336"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/03E1det2dKVsXlhY1Pu8XuRd0LEUGd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/03E1det2dKVsXlhY1Pu8XuRd0LEUGd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":813}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63596"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T17:54:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T17:55:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10254"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78190"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},